<subSubSection id="C3216550FF972961FFE7FD5CFD4704C7" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF972961FFE7FD5CFD4704C7" blockId="1.[113,1089,753,1608]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF972961FFE7FD5CFF3B0307" bold="true" box="[113,232,753,776]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Diagnosis.</emphasis>
Very small, convex above and below, elytra widest just behind middle and narrowing apically; eyes narrowly separated on vertex by less than length of antennomere III; pronotal surface evenly, weakly transversely punctate; elytral surface evenly, moderately punctate, without visible costae or foveae; above submetallic black with shining green, blue, red, and violet markings, head green to blue-green from frons to narrowly behind eyes, black behind, central area of frons golden-green, clypeus blue-green; pronotum with central aeneous reflections, front margin, base, and lateral areas green (blue-green in certain lights); elytra with base and basal two-fifths of suture and lateral margins green (blue-green in certain lights) that are expanded posteriorly, the lateral more strongly so, each elytron with large, red post-median spot that is more violaceous posteriorly, dark area surrounding spot with distinct violaceous reflections, apices bright green, green area extending forward along apical onefourth of suture and along lateral margin to narrowly connect with basal green area; below shining metallic black with lateral green, violet, and red markings; lateral portions of thorax underneath brassy to reddish cupreous, narrowly bright green on abdomen; legs with femora blue to blue-green, tibiae and tarsi dark violaceous.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3216550FF972962FFE7FB7CFC1C0606" lastPageId="2" lastPageNumber="31" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" type="description">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF972961FFE7FB7CFBE804E7" blockId="1.[113,1089,753,1608]" box="[113,1083,1233,1256]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF972961FFE7FB7CFF2F04E7" bold="true" box="[113,252,1233,1256]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Description.</emphasis>
<typeStatus id="54808879FF972961FE95FB7CFEB504E7" box="[259,358,1233,1256]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Holotype</typeStatus>
female (
<figureCitation id="13002A5EFF972961FE52FB7CFDD104E7" box="[452,514,1233,1256]" captionStart="Fig" captionStartId="2.[687,718,987,1006]" captionTargetBox="[204,628,252,1035]" captionTargetId="figure-186@2.[154,656,217,1068]" captionTargetPageId="2" captionText="Fig. 1. Chrysobothris bimaculata sp. nov. Holotype female, dorsal habitus. Scale bar = 1 mm." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468303/files/figure.png" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Fig. 1</figureCitation>
). Size 5.00 mm long × 
<quantity id="4CC39B3EFF972961FD69FB7CFC8E04E7" box="[767,861,1233,1256]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.15" pageId="1" pageNumber="30" unit="mm" value="2.15">2.15 mm</quantity>
wide, subdepressed.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF972961FF06FB5DFBFF0587" blockId="1.[113,1089,753,1608]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF972961FF06FB5DFF180507" bold="true" box="[144,203,1264,1288]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Head</emphasis>
rather evenly shallowly convex, coarsely densely punctate, with an arcuate carina on vertex that ends in a distinct chevron at top of frons and an irregularly transverse callosity at middle; white setae on lower frons short, suberect, longer and subdepressed on clypeus; front margin of clypeus moderately broadly, deeply, arcuately emarginate; antennomere I dark blue, bright green at base, II and III dark violaceous, IV–XI black with brassy reflections.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF972961FF06FA3CFE230647" blockId="1.[113,1089,753,1608]" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF972961FF06FA3CFF2D05A7" bold="true" box="[144,254,1425,1448]" italics="true" pageId="1" pageNumber="30">Pronotum</emphasis>
shallowly evenly convex, vaguely depressed on each side of middle before base; surface with punctures smaller, shallower, and sparser than on head, especially at middle, becoming confused laterally and with transverse rugae developing; front margin broadly, weakly produced at middle; hind margin evenly bisinuate, truncate in front of scutellum; sides slightly swollen, margins entire, nearly straight, front angles broadly triangular; setae short, sparse, barely visible on disk.
</paragraph>
<caption id="DF446653FF942962FD39FC76FBC70406" ID-DOI="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4468303" ID-Zenodo-Dep="4468303" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4468303/files/figure.png" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" startId="2.[687,718,987,1006]" targetBox="[204,628,252,1035]" targetPageId="2">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF942962FD39FC76FBC70406" blockId="2.[687,1126,987,1033]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
Fig. 1. 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF942962FD7AFC76FC1803E1" authority="Macrae, 2016" authorityName="Macrae" authorityYear="2016" box="[748,971,987,1006]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FD7AFC76FC1803E1" box="[748,971,987,1006]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Chrysobothris bimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27C57B2FF942962FC46FC76FBC003E1" box="[976,1043,987,1006]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
Holotype female, dorsal habitus. Scale bar = 1 mm.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF942962FF23FBDCFF310546" blockId="2.[151,1127,1137,1609]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FF23FBDCFF2A0486" bold="true" box="[181,249,1137,1161]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Elytra</emphasis>
distinctly wider than pronotum, constricted basally, widest behind the middle, then gradually evenly converging to moderately rounded apices; basal margins weakly angularly produced at middle, lateral margins distinctly serrate from behind middle to apices; basal depressions distinct, humeral depressions present but shallow; surface without any visible costae; rather evenly moderately shallowly punctate, punctures similar to those on pronotum, becoming finer and sparser apically, setae short, sparse, indistinct; elytra covering eighth tergite.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF942962FF23FAFCFC1C0606" blockId="2.[151,1127,1137,1609]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FF23FAFCFEFC0566" bold="true" box="[181,303,1361,1385]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FF23FAFCFEF40566" bold="true" box="[181,295,1361,1385]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Underside</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Prosternum broadly lobed in front, coarsely densely punctate, with setae moderate, dense, recumbent. Abdomen without lateral callosities, moderately and sparsely punctate, setae long, recumbent; last visible ventrite with lateral margins entire, with weakly developed submarginal ridges, apex with a broad shallow emargination that is limited ventrally by a fine weakly arcuate margin. Anterior femur with a large broadly triangular acute tooth that is not denticulate on outer margin. Anterior tibia slightly arcuate, simple.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3216550FF942963FF01F9BFFE1F027C" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF942963FF01F9BFFE1F027C" blockId="2.[151,1127,1137,1609]" lastBlockId="3.[113,1089,220,851]" lastPageId="3" lastPageNumber="32" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FF01F9BFFE400626" bold="true" box="[151,403,1554,1577]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Differential diagnosis.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF942962FE0DF9BFFD670626" authority="Macrae, 2016" authorityName="Macrae" authorityYear="2016" box="[411,692,1554,1577]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF942962FE0DF9BFFD670626" box="[411,692,1554,1577]" italics="true" pageId="2" pageNumber="31">Chrysobothris bimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27C57B2FF942962FD2AF9BFFCC20626" box="[700,785,1554,1577]" pageId="2" pageNumber="31" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is easily distinguished from all other known West Indian species by the unique pattern of markings on the elytra, in particular the two large round red postmedian spots. From the five other species known from 
<collectingCountry id="F32C764BFF952963FC40FF71FBFF00FC" box="[982,1068,220,243]" name="Jamaica" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
it also differs by the form of the pronotum; widest at the base with the sides straight and slightly converging towards the apex. In 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FE51FEB1FD1A013C" authority="Fisher, 1925" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1925" box="[455,713,284,307]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="insulana">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FE51FEB1FD92013C" box="[455,577,284,307]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. insulana</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B2AFF952963FDD0FEB1FD1A013C" author="FISHER W. S." box="[582,713,284,307]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 207" refId="ref2310" refString="FISHER W. S. 1925: A revision of the West Indian Coleoptera of the family Buprestidae. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 65 (2522): 1 - 207." type="journal article" year="1925">Fisher, 1925</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FD6CFEB1FF06015C" authority="Fisher, 1925" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1925" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="subSpecies" species="sexfasciata" subSpecies="jamaicensis">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FD6CFEB1FBC1013C" box="[762,1042,284,307]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. sexfasciata jamaicensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B2AFF952963FB81FEB1FF06015C" author="FISHER W. S." pageId="3" pageNumber="32" pagination="1 - 207" refId="ref2310" refString="FISHER W. S. 1925: A revision of the West Indian Coleoptera of the family Buprestidae. Proceedings of the United States National Museum 65 (2522): 1 - 207." type="journal article" year="1925">Fisher, 1925</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
the pronotum is widest at the middle with the sides evenly arcuate; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FC5EFE91FF25017C" authority="Fisher, 1930" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1930" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gowdeyi">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FC5EFE91FB92015C" box="[968,1089,316,339]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. gowdeyi</emphasis>
Fisher, 1930
</taxonomicName>
it is widest near the apex with the sides feebly expanded from the base; in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FBBEFEF1FE6F019C" authority="Hoscheck, 1931" authorityName="Hoscheck" authorityYear="1931" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pseudinsularis">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FBBEFEF1FEDE019C" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. pseudinsularis</emphasis>
Hoscheck, 1931
</taxonomicName>
it is widest at the base with the sides evenly arcuate; and in 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FBBEFED1FE0501BC" authority="(Fabricius, 1776)" baseAuthorityName="Fabricius" baseAuthorityYear="1776" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="quadrimaculata">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FBBEFED1FEC801BC" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. quadrimaculata</emphasis>
(Fabricius, 1776)
</taxonomicName>
it is widest and strongly angulate near the apex. It is further distinguished from 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FEA9FE11FE6501DC" authorityName="Fisher" authorityYear="1930" box="[319,438,444,467]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="gowdeyi">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FEA9FE11FE6501DC" box="[319,438,444,467]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">C. gowdeyi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
by the rounded elytral apices not produced into apical spines. 
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FFE7FE71FE4501FC" bold="true" box="[113,406,476,499]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Collecting circumstances.</emphasis>
Nothing is known about the biology of this species. The area around the 
<typeStatus id="54808879FF952963FF79FE51FECE021C" box="[239,285,508,531]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
locality contains some of the island’s few remaining tracts of moist low to middle elevation forest (PECK &amp; KUKALOVA- 
<bibRefCitation id="EFAA4B2AFF952963FDFDFDB1FD30023C" author="PECK S. B. &amp; KUKALOVA-PECK J." box="[619,739,540,563]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" pagination="105 - 116" refId="ref2445" refString="PECK S. B. &amp; KUKALOVA-PECK J. 1975: A guide to natural history field localities in Jamaica. Studies on the Neotropical Fauna 10: 105 - 116." type="journal article" year="1975">PECK 1975</bibRefCitation>
). The single 
<typeStatus id="54808879FF952963FCE4FDB1FC73023C" box="[882,928,540,563]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
specimen was collected by beating leaves on the tops of trees with a butterfly net during the early morning hours (E. Ruzzier, pers. comm.).
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3216550FF952963FFE7FDD1FBD6029C" box="[113,1029,636,659]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF952963FFE7FDD1FBD6029C" blockId="3.[113,1089,220,851]" box="[113,1029,636,659]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FFE7FDD1FF21029C" bold="true" box="[113,242,636,659]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Etymology.</emphasis>
The specific epithet, an adjective, refers to the two large red elytral spots.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3216550FF952963FFE7FD31FD2802BC" box="[113,763,668,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="distribution">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF952963FFE7FD31FD2802BC" blockId="3.[113,1089,220,851]" box="[113,763,668,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FFE7FD31FED702BC" bold="true" box="[113,260,668,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Distribution.</emphasis>
Known only from the 
<typeStatus id="54808879FF952963FE61FD31FDF602BC" box="[503,549,668,691]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">type</typeStatus>
locality in 
<collectingCountry id="F32C764BFF952963FD08FD31FD2402BC" box="[670,759,668,691]" name="Jamaica" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Jamaica</collectingCountry>
.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="C3216550FF952963FFE7FD11FC88035C" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" type="discussion">
<paragraph id="8B8436DBFF952963FFE7FD11FC88035C" blockId="3.[113,1089,220,851]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FFE7FD11FF2002DC" bold="true" box="[113,243,700,723]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Comments.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FF6DFD11FDC702DC" authority="Macrae, 2016" authorityName="Macrae" authorityYear="2016" box="[251,532,700,723]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="bimaculata" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FF6DFD11FDC702DC" box="[251,532,700,723]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Chrysobothris bimaculata</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel id="A27C57B2FF952963FD8BFD11FDA202DC" box="[541,625,700,723]" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
is one of many West Indian species in the genus exhibiting bright red spots or maculae on the elytra or pronotum; otherwise not common in the genus. These are often combined with brilliant metallic green, blue, or violaceous markings, as a result making Carribean 
<taxonomicName id="4C3B4D58FF952963FD8AFCB1FD66033C" authorityName="Eschscholtz" authorityYear="1829" box="[540,693,796,819]" class="Insecta" family="Buprestidae" genus="Chrysobothris" kingdom="Animalia" order="Coleoptera" pageId="3" pageNumber="32" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis id="B94FEAC9FF952963FD8AFCB1FD66033C" box="[540,693,796,819]" italics="true" pageId="3" pageNumber="32">Chrysobothris</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
among the most ornate in the genus. The functional significance of this distinctive color motif is unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
